gone a revolution, moving away from a system based on fresh, locally grown goods to one dominated by packaged foods. How did this come to be? How did we learn to trust that food preserved within an opaque can was safe and desirable to eat? Anna Zeide reveals the answers through the story of the canning industry, taking us on a journey to understand how food industry leaders leveraged the powers of science, marketing, and politics to win over a reluctant public, even as consumers resisted at every turn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCanned foods industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCanned foods industryzUnited Statesy20th century. 0aCanned foodszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCanned foodszUnited Statesy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aamerican history.  aamerican.  acanned food.  acanning industry.  acanning.  aconsumers.  aconsumption.  afactory farming.  afarming.  afood and nutrition.  afood history.  afood preservation.  afood.  ahealth and wellness.  ahealthy food.  ahistory book.  aindustrial.  aindustry.  alocal farmers.  alocal growers.  amarketing.  amass production.  anutrition.  apackaged foods.  apreserving food.  areference book.  arevolution.  ascholarly.  asmall business.  asmall farm.  asustainability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029068640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096475440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964754/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a